{"title":"Bad Form: Comparing Context-Based and Form-Based Few-Shot Learning in Distributional Semantic Models","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Existing few-shot evaluations for learning word embeddings (DN, Chimera, CRW) do not fairly compare context-only and hybrid (form+context) models: hybrid models can exploit lexical leakage from related word forms in the background embeddings, and the Chimera test set is too small for stable comparisons.","method":"Introduce three new evaluation setups: (1) Full Chimera by adding the training set to the test set (330 words) to stabilize results; (2) Filtered DN and (3) Filtered CRW, where background embeddings are trained on a corpus filtered to remove any words sharing a stem with test items, preventing form leakage. An analysis shows many test words have near neighbors with the same stem, and a simple stem-based baseline dominates DN, motivating the filtered tasks and enabling balanced comparisons between context-based and hybrid methods."},{"problem":"Standard few-shot updating with Word2Vec/FastText can distort background embeddings and conflicts with aggressive learning rates; additive/ALC/FCM-style context aggregation treats all tokens uniformly, underusing informative context structure.","method":"Propose selective Word2Vec and selective FastText that update only the target (test) word vector and prevent test words from appearing as negative samples, avoiding background drift and enabling higher-risk learning when beneficial. Further, integrate Word2Vec principles into additive and A La Carte (and thus FCM’s context part): apply sampled window-based distance weights, subsampling weights for frequent words, and adjust sums by subtracting the expected negative sample vector before weighting. With tuned hyperparameters, these simple modifications consistently improve baselines and advanced models across tasks, contributing to new state of the art results on multiple evaluations."},{"problem":"Linear transformations in A La Carte and fixed combination schemes limit adaptability across scenarios with varying amounts of form and context information.","method":"Replace the A La Carte linear map with a one-hidden-layer neural network (ReLU, ~1000 hidden units) trained with Adam and MSE, and use the same neural transformation within a new Neural Form-Context Model. Using the same window-based weighting, these neural variants provide greater flexibility; Neural FCM achieves top performance on the Filtered CRW task and strong results across trials, contributing to several new state-of-the-art scores."}]}
